/* C-Factor Fact of the Day - auto-rotating bank mined from the C-Factor books.
   Rotates deterministically by date; no manual updates needed. */
window.CFACTS=[{"s": "Biology", "t": "CARBON vs SILICON", "b": "Silicon also has four valence electrons, so why is life not silicon based? Because carbon's bonds are the right strength: strong enough to be stable, weak enough to be broken and rebuilt by enzymes at body temperature."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "WHAT SETS MASS vs WHAT SETS CHARGE vs WHAT SETS CHEMISTRY", "b": "MASS is set by the nucleus (protons + neutrons); electrons are negligible. NET CHARGE is set by the proton-to-electron balance: equal numbers means neutral, an excess of electrons means an anion, a deficit means a cation."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "COUNTING GROUPS vs COUNTING ATOMS", "b": "Hybridization is set by the number of electron GROUPS (sigma-bonded atoms PLUS lone pairs), not by the number of atoms alone. The oxygen of water has two bonded hydrogens but also two lone pairs, so four groups: it is sp3, bent."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "SCALAR vs VECTOR", "b": "A SCALAR has magnitude only and adds by ordinary arithmetic: mass, time, temperature, energy, speed, distance. A VECTOR has magnitude AND direction and adds geometrically (tip-to-tail or by components): displacement, velocity, acceleration, force."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Graded Potentials vs. Action Potentials", "b": "Graded potentials and action potentials both change membrane voltage, but they differ in almost every other respect. A graded potential is a local, decremental change in membrane voltage produced by the opening of ligand-gated or mechanically gated channels; its amplitude is proportional to stimulus…"}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "WHICH AMINO ACID ABSORBS AT 280 nm - AND WHY", "b": "Proteins absorb ultraviolet light at 280 nm primarily because of tryptophan and, to a lesser extent, tyrosine. Tryptophan's indole ring has an extended pi-conjugated system with a large extinction coefficient at 280 nm (approximately 5,500 M-1 cm-1 per Trp residue)."}, {"s": "Final Review", "t": "THIS BOOK vs THE PARENT VOLUMES", "b": "The parent volumes (Books 1-6) teach mechanism in depth, with passages, clinical bridges, and full explanatory prose. This book strips that to the bone for retrieval. If you are encountering a concept for the first time here, you are using the book wrong."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "The Cell: Where Non-Life Becomes Life", "b": "The single most important boundary in the hierarchy is the CELL. Everything below it (atoms, molecules, even organelles) is chemistry, not alive on its own. The cell is the smallest unit that is alive, where metabolism, reproduction, and response to the environment all emerge together."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "MASS NUMBER vs ATOMIC MASS vs ATOMIC NUMBER", "b": "ATOMIC NUMBER (Z): a whole number, the proton count, defines the element. MASS NUMBER (A): a whole number, protons plus neutrons, belongs to one specific isotope and appears in isotope notation (e.g., the 14 in carbon-14)."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "SIGMA vs PI BOND", "b": "SIGMA: head-on overlap, electron density ON the internuclear axis, cylindrically symmetric, allows FREE rotation, present in every bond (single, and the first bond of double/triple)."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "WHEN TO USE SINE vs COSINE", "b": "With the angle measured FROM THE HORIZONTAL: the horizontal (adjacent) component uses COSINE, Vx = V cos(θ); the vertical (opposite) component uses SINE, Vy = V sin(θ). If the angle is instead measured FROM THE VERTICAL, the two swap."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Ionotropic vs. Metabotropic Receptors", "b": "Ionotropic receptors are ligand-gated ion channels: the receptor protein itself is the channel. When neurotransmitter binds, the channel opens within microseconds, allowing ions to flow down their electrochemical gradients. The response is fast, local, and brief."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "What Restricts Backbone Flexibility", "b": "PEPTIDE BOND (omega angle): rigid and planar due to resonance delocalization; cannot rotate freely; essentially always trans (>99.9%); the C-N bond has ~40% double bond character."}, {"s": "Final Review", "t": "MITOSIS vs MEIOSIS I vs MEIOSIS II", "b": "MITOSIS: sister chromatids separate, daughters are diploid clones. MEIOSIS I: HOMOLOGOUS chromosomes separate (the reductional division); chromosome number halves. MEIOSIS II: sister chromatids separate (looks like mitosis but on haploid cells). If chromosome number halves, it is meiosis I."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "pKa vs pI", "b": "pKa is a property of a single ionizable GROUP: the pH at which that group is half ionized. pI is a property of the whole MOLECULE: the pH at which it carries no net charge. Compute pI by averaging the two pKa values that bracket the zwitterion."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "PLUM-PUDDING vs NUCLEAR ATOM", "b": "PLUM-PUDDING: positive charge and mass spread uniformly through the whole atomic volume, electrons embedded throughout; predicts almost no large-angle deflection."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "BOND STRENGTH vs ACIDITY (same direction, different reason)", "b": "More s-character makes the C-H bond STRONGER (harder to break homolytically) AND more ACIDIC (easier to lose as H+). These sound contradictory but are not: acidity is about the stability of the conjugate base (the carbanion) AFTER the proton leaves, not about the raw bond strength."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "DISTANCE/SPEED (scalars) vs DISPLACEMENT/VELOCITY (vectors)", "b": "DISTANCE and SPEED are scalars: total path length and its rate, always positive, path-dependent. DISPLACEMENT and VELOCITY are vectors: net change in position and its rate, with direction, depending only on endpoints. Average speed = distance/time; average velocity = displacement/time."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Sympathetic vs. Parasympathetic: Fight-or-Flight vs. Rest-and-Digest", "b": "The sympathetic system mobilizes the body for action. It increases heart rate and contractility (beta-1 receptors on the SA node and myocardium), dilates airways (beta-2 on bronchial smooth muscle), redistributes blood from splanchnic to skeletal muscle (alpha-1 vasoconstriction elsewhere; beta-2 va…"}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "ALPHA HELIX vs BETA SHEET HYDROGEN BONDING", "b": "ALPHA HELIX: hydrogen bonds are within a single polypeptide chain; they run along the helix axis between the backbone C=O of residue i and the backbone N-H of residue i+4; every backbone group (except termini) participates; side chains are NOT involved; the helix is stabilized purely by intramolecul…"}, {"s": "Final Review", "t": "OPERONS (prokaryotes) vs EUKARYOTIC GENE REGULATION", "b": "OPERONS: polycistronic mRNA, regulated as one unit (lac, trp); lac operon induced by allolactose (removes lac repressor) AND glucose absent (cAMP-CAP binds)."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "What Holds Each Level Together", "b": "Primary = covalent peptide bonds. Secondary = hydrogen bonds between BACKBONE atoms (alpha helix, beta sheet), never side chains. Tertiary = R-GROUP interactions, including the only intra-chain covalent crosslink, the disulfide bond. Quaternary = the same R-group forces but between subunits."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "FREQUENCY vs INTENSITY OF LIGHT", "b": "FREQUENCY (equivalently, shorter wavelength) sets the ENERGY PER PHOTON: only frequency above the threshold ejects electrons, and raising frequency raises each ejected electron's energy."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "RESONANCE vs EQUILIBRIUM (the number-one conceptual trap)", "b": "RESONANCE: ONE molecule, ONE real structure (the hybrid); the contributors are drawings that differ only in electron placement; connected by a double-headed arrow; nothing actually moves between them. EQUILIBRIUM: TWO different molecules (different atom positions, e.g."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "AVERAGE vs INSTANTANEOUS", "b": "AVERAGE velocity is displacement divided by the whole time interval; it smooths over everything that happened in between. INSTANTANEOUS velocity is the value at one moment, the slope of the position-time graph at that point and what a speedometer shows."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Afferent vs. Efferent", "b": "Afferent fibers carry sensory information toward the CNS (think: 'a' for 'arriving'). Efferent fibers carry motor commands away from the CNS toward effector organs (think: 'e' for 'exiting')."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "MYOGLOBIN vs HEMOGLOBIN", "b": "MYOGLOBIN: monomer (single polypeptide chain); no quaternary structure; no cooperativity; hyperbolic oxygen binding curve; Hill coefficient n = 1; P50 approximately 1 to 2 mmHg; located in muscle; RECEIVES oxygen from hemoglobin; stores oxygen for mitochondrial use; acts as oxygen buffer during musc…"}, {"s": "Final Review", "t": "RATE-DETERMINING STEP vs OVERALL REACTION", "b": "The rate law reflects only steps up to and including the slowest (rate-determining) step. Fast steps before the RDS contribute via their equilibrium constants. Fast steps after the RDS do not affect the rate law."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "What Disrupts Which Force", "b": "Heat disrupts weak interactions broadly (denaturation). A pH change protonates or deprotonates side chains, specifically breaking IONIC bridges. Reducing agents (like beta-mercaptoethanol) break only DISULFIDE bonds. Detergents and urea disrupt the HYDROPHOBIC core."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "GROUND STATE vs EXCITED STATE vs IONIZATION", "b": "GROUND STATE: the electron in its lowest allowed level (n = 1 for hydrogen), most stable, most tightly bound. EXCITED STATE: the electron has absorbed energy and occupies a higher level (n = 2, 3...); unstable, it will fall back and emit a photon."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "INDUCTIVE EFFECT vs RESONANCE EFFECT", "b": "INDUCTIVE: electron density pulled through the SIGMA bonds by electronegativity; falls off fast with distance; needs no pi system; arises from any electronegative atom."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "VELOCITY vs ACCELERATION", "b": "VELOCITY is how fast and which way an object is moving right now. ACCELERATION is how fast and which way that velocity is CHANGING. They are independent: an object can have large velocity and zero acceleration (cruising at constant speed in a straight line) or zero velocity and large acceleration (t…"}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Broca's Area vs. Wernicke's Area: Production vs. Comprehension Aphasia", "b": "Both areas are in the left hemisphere in approximately 95% of right-handed individuals and about 70% of left-handed individuals; left hemisphere language dominance is the rule. Broca's area (left inferior frontal gyrus) is involved in speech production and the motor programming of articulation."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "PRION vs TYPICAL INFECTIOUS AGENT", "b": "TYPICAL INFECTIOUS AGENT (virus, bacterium, fungus, parasite): requires nucleic acid (DNA or RNA) to encode its own proteins; can be killed by methods that destroy nucleic acids (UV irradiation, nucleases, heat that hydrolyzes nucleic acids); treatment with standard autoclaving (121 °C, 15 psi, 20 m…"}, {"s": "Final Review", "t": "GALVANIC vs ELECTROLYTIC CELL", "b": "BOTH: anode = oxidation, cathode = reduction, electrons flow anode → cathode in wire. GALVANIC: spontaneous, generates current, anode is the NEGATIVE terminal (electrons leaving), cathode positive."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "DENATURATION vs MISFOLDING vs MUTATION", "b": "Denaturation: an already-correct protein loses its higher-order shape (heat, pH, urea), usually with the sequence intact and sometimes reversible. Misfolding: the chain reaches a wrong stable shape, as in amyloid and prion disease, with a normal or near-normal sequence."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "EMISSION vs ABSORPTION SPECTRUM", "b": "EMISSION: an excited atom releases photons as electrons fall to lower levels; seen as bright lines on a dark background. ABSORPTION: ground-state atoms remove photons from passing white light as electrons climb to higher levels; seen as dark lines on a continuous rainbow."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "Ranking The Five Factors When They Compete", "b": "When more than one factor applies, ATOM (across a period) and RESONANCE are usually the largest effects, and a difference in either typically decides the ranking. INDUCTION and ORBITAL are smaller, acting as tiebreakers when the atom and resonance situations are similar."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "Which Kinematic Equation To Pick", "b": "List the five quantities (x, v0, v, a, t). Mark what you KNOW and what you WANT. The fourth quantity, the one you neither know nor want, tells you which equation to use, because each equation omits exactly one variable. No time given and none wanted? Use v2 = v0^2 + 2 a x."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "What Heritability Does and Does Not Mean", "b": "A common MCAT distractor: high heritability implies genetic determinism or that environment does not matter. Both are false. Consider height, with a heritability of approximately 0.80 in well-nourished Western populations."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "OSTEOGENESIS IMPERFECTA vs EHLERS-DANLOS SYNDROME", "b": "Both are collagen diseases; the distinction is the mechanism and presentation. OSTEOGENESIS IMPERFECTA: the primary defect is in collagen TYPE I STRUCTURE - specifically, substitution of the mandatory glycine residue in the Gly-X-Y triple helix; the result is structurally defective collagen that can…"}, {"s": "Final Review", "t": "ORTHO/PARA vs META DIRECTORS", "b": "Ortho/para directors stabilize the arenium ion intermediate at ortho or para positions through resonance (donating groups put a lone pair in conjugation with the ring) or by hyperconjugation (alkyl groups)."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "HEMOGLOBIN vs MYOGLOBIN", "b": "Hemoglobin: four subunits (quaternary structure), cooperative binding, sigmoidal (S-shaped) curve, regulated by pH, CO2, and 2,3-BPG, built to LOAD oxygen in the lungs and UNLOAD it in tissue."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "ORBIT (BOHR) vs ORBITAL (QUANTUM MODEL)", "b": "ORBIT: a definite circular path at a fixed radius, electron treated as a particle with known position and momentum; the Bohr picture, which only works for one-electron systems and violates the uncertainty principle."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "Which Way The Proton Goes", "b": "A proton transfer favors forming the WEAKER acid (HIGHER pKa) and the more stable conjugate base. To deprotonate an acid completely you need a base whose conjugate acid has a HIGHER pKa than the acid you are trying to remove the proton from."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "At The Peak: Velocity Zero, Acceleration Not", "b": "At the top of a vertical throw the VELOCITY is zero for an instant, but the ACCELERATION is still g 2 downward (about 9.8 or 10 m/s ). This is the classic trap."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Neuroimaging: Correlation vs. Causation", "b": "A patient with a stroke lesion to Broca's area has non-fluent aphasia. An fMRI study finds that Broca's area activates when healthy subjects produce speech. These two results converge on the same structure, but they carry very different inferential weight."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "ALPHA-1 ANTITRYPSIN DEFICIENCY vs CYSTIC FIBROSIS", "b": "Both diseases involve protein misfolding and failure of a protein to reach its normal cellular location, but the protein, the site of retention, and the target organ logic differ."}, {"s": "Final Review", "t": "ALPHA vs BETA ANOMERS (sugars)", "b": "Anomers differ only at the anomeric carbon (the former carbonyl C). In D-sugars drawn in standard Haworth projection, ALPHA has the anomeric -OH down (trans to the CH2OH at C5 in glucose), BETA has it up."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "COLLAGEN vs ELASTIN vs FIBRILLIN (a classic trap)", "b": "Collagen gives tensile strength (Gly-X-Y triple helix); defects cause osteogenesis imperfecta and most Ehlers-Danlos. Elastin gives stretch and recoil to lungs, large arteries, and skin, and is rich in proline and glycine but not hydroxylated or glycosylated like collagen."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "What Each Quantum Number Actually Specifies", "b": "n = SHELL (energy and size). l = SUBSHELL (shape: s, p, d, f). m_l = the SPECIFIC ORBITAL and its orientation within that subshell. m_s = the electron's SPIN. The most common error is confusing l (shape, the subshell) with m_l (orientation, the individual orbital)."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "NUCLEOPHILE vs BASE (and ELECTROPHILE vs ACID)", "b": "A NUCLEOPHILE donates electrons to a CARBON (forming a bond, a kinetic property about rate); a BASE donates electrons to a PROTON (an acid-base, thermodynamic property)."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "HORIZONTAL vs VERTICAL MOTION IN A PROJECTILE", "b": "HORIZONTAL: no acceleration (air resistance ignored), so velocity is CONSTANT; use x = Vx t. VERTICAL: acceleration g downward, so it is free fall; use the kinematic equations with a = -g. The two share ONLY the time t."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "SENSATION vs PERCEPTION", "b": "SENSATION is the detection and transduction of physical energy by a receptor; it is essentially mechanical and operates the same way regardless of context, expectation, or prior experience."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "ENZYME EFFECT ON Ea vs ∆G vs Keq", "b": "An enzyme LOWERS the activation energy (Ea) for both the forward and reverse reactions equally. It does NOT change: (1) the standard free-energy change (∆G°) of the reaction - whether the reaction is exergonic or endergonic is determined by the thermodynamics of substrates and products, not by the e…"}, {"s": "Final Review", "t": "INTENSITY vs FREQUENCY (photoelectric effect)", "b": "Classical physics predicted that brighter light (higher intensity) should give higher-energy electrons. The photoelectric effect showed otherwise: FREQUENCY (not intensity) determines whether and how energetically electrons are ejected; INTENSITY determines how MANY electrons are ejected (once above…"}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "SICKLE CELL vs THALASSEMIA", "b": "Sickle cell is a QUALITATIVE defect: normal amount of beta-globin, wrong amino acid (Glu->Val), a point (missense) mutation. Thalassemia is a QUANTITATIVE defect: structurally normal globin, too little of it, often from splicing or deletion mutations."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "NUMBER OF ORBITALS vs NUMBER OF ELECTRONS", "b": "A subshell's ORBITAL count is 2l+1 (s:1, p:3, d:5, f:7). Its ELECTRON capacity is twice that (s:2, p:6, d:10, f:14) because each orbital holds two electrons of opposite spin. Do not conflate them: a p subshell has three orbitals but six electrons."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "Arrow Tail On Electrons, Not On The Atom Or The Proton", "b": "The tail of a curved arrow must start on the ELECTRONS that move (a lone pair or a bond), never on a positive charge or on the atom or proton itself. To show a base grabbing a proton, the arrow goes FROM the base's lone pair TO the hydrogen, never from the hydrogen to the base."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "DROPPED vs LAUNCHED HORIZONTALLY (the simultaneous-landing trap)", "b": "A ball dropped from a height and an identical ball fired horizontally from the same height hit the ground AT THE SAME TIME, because both have zero initial vertical velocity and identical vertical free fall."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "SENSITIVITY (d') vs RESPONSE BIAS (CRITERION)", "b": "d' (d-prime) is a measure of true sensory SENSITIVITY — how well an observer's nervous system can detect the presence of a signal amid background noise. It depends on the physical and neural characteristics of the observer's sensory apparatus."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "HOLOENZYME vs APOENZYME vs COENZYME vs PROSTHETIC GROUP", "b": "APOENZYME: the protein component of an enzyme without its cofactor; catalytically INACTIVE. HOLOENZYME: apoenzyme + cofactor(s); catalytically ACTIVE. COENZYME: organic, non-protein cofactor that binds loosely; acts as a co-substrate (accepts or donates a chemical group and is regenerated separately…"}, {"s": "Final Review", "t": "CLASSICAL vs OPERANT CONDITIONING", "b": "CLASSICAL pairs two stimuli to elicit an automatic response (Pavlov: bell + food → bell alone causes salivation). The behavior is REFLEXIVE and elicited. OPERANT pairs a behavior with a consequence to change its frequency (Skinner: rat presses lever → gets food → presses more)."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "WHAT AN ENZYME CHANGES vs WHAT IT DOES NOT", "b": "CHANGES: the rate (kinetics), by lowering activation energy and stabilizing the transition state. DOES NOT CHANGE: the equilibrium constant (Keq), the overall free-energy change (delta G), or whether the reaction is spontaneous (thermodynamics)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "AUFBAU vs PAULI vs HUND", "b": "AUFBAU: fill lowest-energy orbitals first (the overall order). PAULI: at most two electrons per orbital and they must have opposite spins (no two electrons share all four quantum numbers)."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "STRONG ACID -> WEAK CONJUGATE BASE (and the trap of conflating them)", "b": "The conjugate base of a STRONG acid is WEAK, and the conjugate base of a WEAK acid is STRONG. Chloride (from HCl, a strong acid) is a terrible base; amide ion (from ammonia, a very weak acid) is a ferocious base."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "SLOPE vs AREA (the graph-reading trap)", "b": "SLOPE moves you UP the chain to the rate of change: slope of position-time is velocity; slope of velocity-time is acceleration. AREA moves you DOWN the chain to the accumulated quantity: area under acceleration-time is the velocity change; area under velocity-time is the displacement."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "RODS vs CONES", "b": "RODS: approximately 120 million per retina; located predominantly in the peripheral retina; contain rhodopsin (a single photopigment); maximally sensitive at ~498 nm; function in dim (scotopic) light conditions; highly convergent onto ganglion cells (many rods → one cell), giving high sensitivity bu…"}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "Km vs Kd vs SUBSTRATE AFFINITY", "b": "Km is the substrate concentration at which v = Vmax/2. It is NOT the same as Kd (the true dissociation constant of the ES complex) unless kcat << k-1. In the general steady-state model: Km = (k-1 + kcat) / k1."}, {"s": "Final Review", "t": "JAMES-LANGE vs CANNON-BARD vs SCHACHTER-SINGER", "b": "JAMES-LANGE: body comes first, emotion is the perception of bodily change ('I run, therefore I fear'). CANNON-BARD: body and emotion happen simultaneously and independently. SCHACHTER-SINGER (two-factor): you need both arousal and a cognitive label to have a specific emotion."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "COUPLING vs CATALYSIS", "b": "Catalysis (what an enzyme does alone) changes only the RATE and never makes an unfavorable reaction favorable. Coupling changes the THERMODYNAMICS by summing two reactions, using ATP to pay for an endergonic step."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "VALENCE vs CORE ELECTRONS", "b": "VALENCE electrons live in the highest principal energy level (the outermost shell), are few, are loosely held, and do all the chemistry: bonding, ionization, reactivity. CORE electrons are the inner electrons in the noble-gas configuration, are tightly held, and are chemically inert."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "CONJUGATED vs ISOLATED vs AROMATIC", "b": "ISOLATED double bonds: separated by one or more sp3 carbons; no through-conjugation; behave independently. CONJUGATED: alternating double/single bonds with continuous overlapping p orbitals; pi electrons delocalize over the stretch; extra stability."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "A CURVED vs STRAIGHT POSITION-TIME GRAPH", "b": "A STRAIGHT line on a position-time graph means constant velocity (constant slope, zero acceleration). A CURVED line means the velocity is changing, so there is acceleration. Curving to steeper means speeding up; curving toward flat means slowing down."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "PLACE THEORY vs FREQUENCY (VOLLEY) THEORY OF PITCH", "b": "PLACE THEORY (Helmholtz, elaborated by von Békésy): pitch is encoded by WHICH part of the basilar membrane vibrates maximally. High-frequency tones → base of cochlea (narrow, stiff). Low-frequency tones → apex (wide, flexible). Supported by tonotopic organization of auditory cortex."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "COMPETITIVE vs UNCOMPETITIVE vs NONCOMPETITIVE INHIBITION", "b": "COMPETITIVE: binds FREE enzyme at active site; Km↑ (apparent), Vmax unchanged; Lineweaver-Burk: same y-intercept (1/Vmax), different slope/x-intercept; OVERCOME by high [S]. Example: statins vs HMG-CoA; methotrexate vs dihydrofolate reductase."}, {"s": "Final Review", "t": "ETC INHIBITORS vs UNCOUPLERS vs ATP SYNTHASE INHIBITORS", "b": "ETC INHIBITORS (rotenone, cyanide): stop electron flow; gradient collapses; no ATP. UNCOUPLERS + (2,4-DNP, thermogenin): electrons flow but H leaks back without making ATP → all energy as heat; O2 consumption stays high."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "STABILIZING THE SUBSTRATE vs THE TRANSITION STATE", "b": "An enzyme that bound its substrate too tightly would actually be a worse catalyst, because it would sit in a deep well and need even more energy to climb out toward products."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "PARAMAGNETIC vs DIAMAGNETIC", "b": "PARAMAGNETIC: at least one UNPAIRED electron; attracted INTO a magnetic field. DIAMAGNETIC: all electrons PAIRED; weakly repelled by a magnetic field. The deciding step is the orbital diagram with Hund's rule, not just the configuration string: a filled p6 or d10 is diamagnetic, but a p3 or d6 has u…"}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "The Five Cues That Decide Acidity Questions", "b": "Different ATOM holding the charge -> use electronegativity (across a period) or size (down a group). A conjugate base with a neighboring pi system or carbonyl -> RESONANCE, usually the biggest swing. Electronegative groups nearby -> INDUCTION, a tiebreaker that fades with distance."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "Velocity Is Frame-Dependent", "b": "There is no single 'true' velocity of an object; velocity is always RELATIVE to a chosen frame. To convert between frames, ADD the velocity of the object in one frame to the velocity of that frame relative to the other, as vectors. Same direction: magnitudes add. Opposite: they subtract."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "A-DELTA vs C FIBER PAIN", "b": "A-DELTA FIBERS: lightly myelinated; diameter ~2-5 µm; conduction velocity ~5-30 m/s; encode FIRST pain — sharp, pricking, well-localized, immediate; mediate the fast reflexive withdrawal response to a damaging stimulus."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "HYPERBOLIC vs SIGMOIDAL KINETICS", "b": "HYPERBOLIC v vs [S] curve: characteristic of MICHAELIS-MENTEN (non-allosteric) enzymes; Hill coefficient n = 1; Km is well-defined as the [S] at half-Vmax; the curve is asymptotically smooth. SIGMOIDAL v vs [S] curve: characteristic of ALLOSTERIC, COOPERATIVE enzymes; Hill coefficient n > 1; K ."}, {"s": "Final Review", "t": "DE NOVO vs SALVAGE NUCLEOTIDE SYNTHESIS", "b": "DE NOVO: builds nucleotides from scratch (small precursors: amino acids, CO , formate); energy-expensive, 2 used in dividing cells. SALVAGE: recycles free bases via HGPRT (purines) or APRT; uses much less energy."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "Km vs Vmax", "b": "Km is about AFFINITY and is independent of enzyme amount: it is the substrate concentration at half-maximal velocity, and LOW Km means HIGH affinity. Vmax is about CAPACITY and is proportional to enzyme amount: it is the ceiling velocity at saturation."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "STABLE vs RADIOACTIVE ISOTOPE", "b": "STABLE isotope: a proton-neutron combination inside the band of nuclear stability; it does not decay, and its chemistry is ordinary. RADIOACTIVE (unstable) isotope: a combination outside that band; it spontaneously decays toward stability, emitting radiation, while its chemistry remains identical to…"}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "WHAT IS DRAWN vs WHAT IS IMPLIED", "b": "DRAWN explicitly: every carbon vertex (as a corner, not a letter), every bond, every heteroatom, and every hydrogen bonded to a heteroatom (O-H, N-H, S-H). IMPLIED and never drawn: hydrogens bonded to carbon, and the carbons at plain line ends and bends."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "The Questions That Decide Kinematics Items", "b": "Is the quantity a scalar or a vector? (direction matters or not). Average or instantaneous? (whole interval or one point). Which kinematic variable is missing? (picks the equation). Slope or area? (rate versus total on a graph)."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "BINOCULAR vs MONOCULAR DEPTH CUES", "b": "BINOCULAR CUES require input from both eyes simultaneously. (1) Retinal disparity: the difference in the position of an object's image on the two retinas; large disparity = near; small disparity = far. The basis of stereopsis and 3-D cinema technology."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "PHOSPHORYLATION vs ALLOSTERIC REGULATION vs ZYMOGEN ACTIVATION", "b": "Three regulatory mechanisms differ fundamentally in speed, reversibility, and type of conformational change. ALLOSTERIC REGULATION: non-covalent; nearly instantaneous (ligand binding/release in milliseconds); fully reversible on the timescale of ligand dissociation; mediates moment-to-moment metabol…"}, {"s": "Final Review", "t": "KETOGENIC vs GLUCOGENIC AMINO ACIDS", "b": "KETOGENIC ONLY (Leu, Lys): produce only acetyl-CoA or acetoacetyl-CoA; CANNOT net produce glucose because acetyl-CoA → 2 CO2 in TCA without net carbon gain. GLUCOGENIC: produce pyruvate or TCA intermediates (other than acetyl-CoA), which can enter gluconeogenesis. BOTH: Phe, Tyr, Trp, Ile, Thr."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "Reading The Lineweaver-Burk Plot", "b": "y-intercept = 1/Vmax, so a HIGHER y-intercept means a LOWER Vmax. x-intercept = -1/Km, so an x-intercept closer to zero (less negative) means a LARGER Km (lower affinity)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "NUCLEAR CHARGE vs EFFECTIVE NUCLEAR CHARGE", "b": "NUCLEAR CHARGE is the full positive charge of the nucleus, equal to the number of protons (Z). EFFECTIVE NUCLEAR CHARGE is the reduced net charge a particular electron actually feels after inner electrons shield it, roughly Z minus the shielding electrons."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "What Counts For Alphabetizing", "b": "IGNORED when alphabetizing (they are just counters or location-tags): the multiplying prefixes di, tri, tetra, and the italicized positional prefixes sec- and tert-. So tert-butyl alphabetizes under b. COUNTED when alphabetizing (they are fused into the substituent name): iso and neo and cyclo."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "A SINGLE FORCE vs THE NET FORCE", "b": "A SINGLE force is one push or pull from one source (gravity, a hand, a rope). The NET force is the vector SUM of all forces acting on the object. Only the net force determines acceleration. A common trap is to use the largest single force, or the applied force, in F = ma."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Cs, Us, Cr, Ur — What Each Is", "b": "The US (unconditioned stimulus) elicits a REFLEXIVE, UNLEARNED response. The UR (unconditioned response) IS that reflexive response; it requires no learning. Together, the US-UR pair is the wired-in biology."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "SYNTHASE vs SYNTHETASE vs KINASE vs PHOSPHATASE", "b": "SYNTHASE: an enzyme that catalyzes synthesis, often using the energy of an already-formed high-energy intermediate (e.g., ATP synthase uses the proton gradient; fatty acid synthase uses malonyl-ACP); NOT necessarily ATP-dependent. Examples: ATP synthase, fatty acid synthase, citrate synthase."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "COMPETITIVE vs NONCOMPETITIVE (the one they always ask)", "b": "Competitive: binds the ACTIVE SITE, looks like substrate, beaten by MORE substrate, so Vmax is UNCHANGED but Km RISES. Noncompetitive: binds ELSEWHERE (allosteric), not beaten by substrate, so Vmax FALLS and Km is UNCHANGED."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "The Cues That Decide Atomic-Structure Questions", "b": "Whole-number proton count = atomic number (element). Decimal on the table = abundance-weighted atomic mass. Bright lines = emission (falling); dark lines in a rainbow = absorption (rising). Threshold that intensity cannot overcome = photoelectric, so frequency sets per-photon energy."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "cis/trans vs E/Z", "b": "cis/trans compares the position of the two parent-chain continuations (or the two like groups) across the double bond: same side = cis, opposite = trans. It only works cleanly when each alkene carbon bears one H or one obvious reference group."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "Force Causes Acceleration, Not Velocity", "b": "A net force produces ACCELERATION (a change in velocity), not velocity itself. An object moving at constant velocity has ZERO net force. An object momentarily at rest can have a large net force (a tossed ball at its peak still feels gravity and is accelerating downward at g even though its speed is…"}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "POSITIVE vs NEGATIVE REINFORCEMENT vs PUNISHMENT", "b": "The two dimensions are INDEPENDENT. REINFORCEMENT vs PUNISHMENT: does the behavior INCREASE (reinforcement) or DECREASE (punishment)? POSITIVE vs NEGATIVE: is a stimulus ADDED (positive) or REMOVED (negative)? The matrix: (1) Positive reinforcement: add appetitive stimulus → behavior increases."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "ALPHA vs BETA ANOMERS - WHICH IS MORE STABLE?", "b": "For D-glucose specifically: the BETA anomer is more stable in solution (approximately 64% at equilibrium) because the C1 hydroxyl occupies an EQUATORIAL position in the chair conformation, minimizing 1,3-diaxial interactions with the C3 and C5 ring substituents."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "ALLOSTERIC vs ACTIVE-SITE (COMPETITIVE) BINDING", "b": "An allosteric regulator binds a SEPARATE regulatory site and changes the enzyme's shape, and it can be an activator or an inhibitor. A competitive inhibitor binds the ACTIVE site and can only inhibit."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "ATOMIC NUMBER vs ATOMIC WEIGHT (what the table is ordered by)", "b": "The modern table is ordered by ATOMIC NUMBER (proton count, Z), not atomic weight. Mendeleev originally used weight and had to override it in a few places to keep families together; Moseley showed atomic number was the real ordering quantity, which removed every anomaly at once."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "SUFFIX vs PREFIX (the decision that organizes the whole name)", "b": "SUFFIX: the single highest-priority functional group present; it sets the parent chain, gets the lowest locant, and appears at the END of the name (-oic acid, -al, -one, -ol)."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "ACTION-REACTION PAIR vs BALANCED FORCES ON ONE OBJECT", "b": "An ACTION-REACTION pair: equal, opposite, SAME interaction, but acting on TWO different objects; they never cancel and never appear together in one free-body diagram. BALANCED forces: two forces on the SAME object that happen to be equal and opposite, whose net is zero."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Schedules Of Reinforcement", "b": "Four schedules, two dimensions (ratio/interval, fixed/variable). RATIO schedules reinforce after a NUMBER OF RESPONSES; INTERVAL schedules reinforce the first response after a TIME PERIOD. FIXED schedules use a predictable number/time; VARIABLE use unpredictable."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "REDUCING vs NON-REDUCING SUGARS", "b": "A reducing sugar is one that can act as a reducing agent - it does so through its FREE ANOMERIC CARBON (C1-OH for aldoses), which can open to the aldehyde form and be oxidized by Cu2+ in Benedict's or Fehling's solution."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "HYPERBOLIC (MICHAELIS-MENTEN) vs SIGMOIDAL (COOPERATIVE)", "b": "Hyperbolic curve: a typical single-site enzyme; velocity rises and plateaus smoothly; described by Km and Vmax. Sigmoidal curve: a multi-subunit cooperative enzyme (like hemoglobin's binding curve); S-shaped, acts as a threshold switch, and is shifted by allosteric regulators."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "Z_eff ACROSS vs DOWN (the two motions that explain everything)", "b": "ACROSS a period (left to right): protons added, electrons added to the SAME shell that shield poorly, so Z_eff RISES sharply and outer electrons are held tighter."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "ALCOHOL vs ETHER vs EPOXIDE (all carry one oxygen)", "b": "ALCOHOL: oxygen bonded to one carbon and one hydrogen (C-O-H); a hydrogen-bond DONOR and acceptor; reactive, convertible. ETHER: oxygen bonded to two carbons (C-O-C); no O-H, so an acceptor only; sleepy and used as a solvent."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "MASS vs WEIGHT", "b": "MASS: amount of matter and measure of inertia; scalar; kilograms; SAME everywhere; appears in F = ma as the resistance to acceleration. WEIGHT: the gravitational FORCE on the mass; vector (points down); newtons; CHANGES with local g; equals mg."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "EXPLICIT vs IMPLICIT MEMORY — WITH THE H.M. CASE", "b": "EXPLICIT memory requires CONSCIOUS ACCESS; the person knows they are remembering and can verbally report the memory. It includes EPISODIC (personal events with spatiotemporal context) and SEMANTIC (general knowledge) memory. BOTH depend on the HIPPOCAMPUS for initial encoding."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "HEXOKINASE vs GLUCOKINASE", "b": "Both enzymes phosphorylate glucose at C6 using ATP. The critical differences: HEXOKINASE: low Km (~0.1 mM) = high affinity for glucose; works even at fasting blood glucose levels; inhibited by its product G6P (product inhibition); hyperbolic kinetics; expressed ubiquitously in ALL tissues."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "Vmax vs kcat vs kcat/Km", "b": "Vmax: speed of the whole sample at saturation; depends on enzyme AMOUNT. kcat (turnover number): reactions per second per single active site at saturation; independent of amount, measures intrinsic SPEED."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "CATION vs ANION vs ISOELECTRONIC ORDERING", "b": "CATION < neutral atom: fewer electrons, often a lost shell, higher pull per electron, so it SHRINKS. ANION > neutral atom: extra electrons, more repulsion, same nucleus, so it SWELLS."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "The Carbonyl Family At A Glance", "b": "ALDEHYDE: C=O with an H (RCHO), terminal, suffix -al. KETONE: C=O between two carbons (RCOR'), suffix -one. CARBOXYLIC ACID: C=O plus OH (RCOOH), acidic, suffix -oic acid. ESTER: C=O plus OR (RCOOR'), suffix -oate, named alcohol-part-first then acid-part. AMIDE: C=O plus N (RCONR2), suffix -amide."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "FORCES ON THE OBJECT vs FORCES BY THE OBJECT", "b": "A free-body diagram shows only forces acting ON the chosen object. Forces the object exerts on other things (your foot on the ground, the book on the table) belong on the OTHER object's diagram, not this one."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "RECALL vs RECOGNITION", "b": "RECALL requires generating information from memory with minimal external cues: 'What are the four types of reinforcement schedules?' Both the retrieval process and the construction of the answer must be performed internally."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "PFK-1 vs PFK-2", "b": "PFK-1: the GLYCOLYTIC ENZYME. Converts F6P + ATP → F1,6BP + ADP. RATE-LIMITING step of glycolysis. Regulated allosterically. PFK-2 (= FBPase-2): a BIFUNCTIONAL REGULATORY ENZYME. Its kinase domain converts F6P + ATP → F2,6BP (activates PFK-1)."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "FIRST-ORDER vs ZERO-ORDER ELIMINATION", "b": "First-order (most drugs, [drug] below Km): a constant FRACTION removed per unit time; rate rises with concentration; half-life is constant. Zero-order (saturated enzyme, [drug] above Km): a constant AMOUNT removed per unit time; rate is fixed at Vmax; half-life is not constant and rises with dose."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "The Successive-Ionization Jump Reveals The Group", "b": "Each ionization costs more than the last, but the DRAMATIC jump comes when the next electron must be pulled from the noble-gas CORE. The number of relatively easy ionizations BEFORE that jump equals the number of valence electrons, which equals the group (for main-group elements)."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "ESTER NAMING vs ETHER NAMING (do not confuse the two)", "b": "ESTER (RCOOR'): a carbonyl plus an oxygen-linked carbon; named in TWO words, alkyl part first then acid part with -oate (ethyl butanoate). It has a C=O."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "STATIC vs KINETIC FRICTION", "b": "STATIC friction (no sliding yet) is a VARIABLE force, equal to whatever is needed to prevent motion, up to a MAXIMUM of mu_s*N. Below that maximum it is less than mu_s*N. KINETIC friction (surfaces sliding) is roughly CONSTANT at mu_k*N and opposes the sliding direction."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "PROACTIVE vs RETROACTIVE INTERFERENCE", "b": "Both involve one memory disrupting another through shared retrieval cues. The distinction is TEMPORAL DIRECTION. PROACTIVE INTERFERENCE (PI): OLD material interferes with NEW. The direction is forward in time: the old memory proactively (going forward) disrupts retrieval of the new one."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "Pdh Complex Cofactors - The Five Vitamins", "b": "The PDH complex requires FIVE coenzymes, each from a different vitamin: 1. TPP (thiamine pyrophosphate) - from vitamin B1 (thiamine); used by E1 for decarboxylation 2. Lipoic acid - not a classic vitamin but an essential cofactor; covalently bound to E2 3."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "The Five Words That Decide Inhibitor Questions", "b": "Resembles substrate + active site = competitive (Km up, Vmax same, beatable). Does not resemble + allosteric = noncompetitive (Vmax down, Km same, not beatable). Binds only ES complex = uncompetitive (both down). Covalent/permanent = irreversible (Vmax down, needs new enzyme)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "IONIZATION ENERGY vs ELECTRON AFFINITY (don't confuse the two)", "b": "IONIZATION ENERGY: energy to REMOVE an electron the atom already has; always costs energy; measures how tightly an atom holds its own electrons. ELECTRON AFFINITY: energy released or absorbed when an atom GAINS an electron; for eager acceptors it releases energy; measures how badly an atom wants an…"}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "CARBON CLASS vs AMINE CLASS", "b": "CARBON / ALCOHOL / HALIDE / CARBOCATION class counts how many CARBONS surround the carbon of interest: 1 degree = one carbon neighbor, up to 4 degree = quaternary (four carbon neighbors, no H)."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "Which Component Gets Sine, Which Gets Cosine", "b": "On an incline of angle theta (measured from the horizontal): the component of gravity ALONG the incline (down the slope) is mg*sin(θ); the component PERPENDICULAR to the incline (into the surface, setting the normal force) is mg*cos(θ)."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "ANTEROGRADE vs RETROGRADE AMNESIA", "b": "ANTEROGRADE AMNESIA is the inability to form NEW memories AFTER the point of injury. Events that occur after the brain damage cannot be encoded into long-term memory. The person cannot learn new faces, new facts, or remember what they had for breakfast this morning."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "Succinate Dehydrogenase - Tca Enzyme And Complex Ii", "b": "Succinate dehydrogenase (SDH) is the ONLY enzyme that is simultaneously a TCA CYCLE enzyme (Step 6: succinate → fumarate + FADH2) and a component of the ELECTRON TRANSPORT CHAIN (Complex II: FADH2 → CoQ)."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "ALDOSE vs KETOSE", "b": "An ALDOSE has its carbonyl (C=O) at carbon 1, as an aldehyde at the end of the chain (glucose, galactose). A KETOSE has its carbonyl at carbon 2, as a ketone inside the chain (fructose). Same atoms, different placement."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "ELECTRON AFFINITY vs ELECTRONEGATIVITY", "b": "ELECTRON AFFINITY is a measured energy for a FREE atom gaining a FREE electron in the gas phase. ELECTRONEGATIVITY is a relative, unitless tendency of a BONDED atom to pull SHARED electrons toward itself within a molecule."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "CONSTITUTIONAL ISOMERS vs STEREOISOMERS", "b": "CONSTITUTIONAL (structural) isomers differ in CONNECTIVITY: what is bonded to what is genuinely different, so they get different parent/prefix/suffix names (butane vs isobutane)."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "CENTRIPETAL FORCE vs THE FICTIONAL CENTRIFUGAL FORCE", "b": "CENTRIPETAL force is real, points INWARD (toward the center), and is supplied by an identifiable force (tension, gravity, friction, normal). The outward CENTRIFUGAL force is NOT a real force; it is an artifact of analyzing motion from a rotating (non-inertial) frame."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "ENCODING FAILURE vs STORAGE DECAY vs RETRIEVAL FAILURE", "b": "Three distinct reasons why a memory cannot be produced. ENCODING FAILURE: the information was never adequately transferred to long-term memory. No trace exists to retrieve. Prevented by: deep processing, elaborative encoding, attention, distributed practice."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "LACTIC ACIDOSIS TYPE A vs TYPE B", "b": "Lactic acidosis (serum lactate > 5 mmol/L + pH < 7.35) is divided by etiology: TYPE A (tissue hypoperfusion/hypoxia): most common; caused by shock (septic, cardiogenic, hemorrhagic), severe anemia, carbon monoxide poisoning, cyanide poisoning."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "ENANTIOMER vs DIASTEREOMER vs EPIMER", "b": "ENANTIOMERS: mirror images, differ at ALL chiral centers (D- vs L-glucose). DIASTEREOMERS: differ at SOME but not all chiral centers. EPIMER (a special diastereomer): differ at EXACTLY ONE chiral center (glucose vs galactose at C4; glucose vs mannose at C2)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "THE INVERSE WEB (which trends point where)", "b": "Toward the TOP-RIGHT (excluding noble gases): high Z_eff, so SMALL radius, HIGH ionization energy, HIGH electron affinity, HIGH electronegativity, LOW metallic character (nonmetals)."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "CHIRAL MOLECULE vs ACHIRAL MOLECULE", "b": "A molecule is CHIRAL if it is not superimposable on its mirror image; it is ACHIRAL if it is. The single most reliable test for achirality is an internal plane of symmetry (or other improper symmetry): if a molecule has an internal mirror plane in any reasonable conformation, it is achiral, full sto…"}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "The Inverse-Square Law In Action", "b": "Gravitational force scales as 1/r2, where r is the center-to-center distance. DOUBLE r → force becomes 1/4; TRIPLE r → 1/9; HALVE r → force becomes 4 times larger. Mass dependence is linear: doubling either mass doubles the force."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "PROTOTYPE THEORY vs EXEMPLAR THEORY", "b": "PROTOTYPE THEORY stores an idealized average example of the category and classifies new instances by their distance from that ideal. It predicts typicality effects (typical instances are classified faster) and is efficient for common, well-defined categories."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "∆G° (STANDARD) vs ∆G (ACTUAL)", "b": "∆G°' is a constant for a given reaction at a given temperature and pH - it describes the reaction when all species are at 1 M concentration. It tells you about the intrinsic thermodynamic properties of the reaction."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "ALPHA vs BETA ANOMER (the highest-yield geometry in carb chemistry)", "b": "At the anomeric carbon (C1 in glucose), the hydroxyl points DOWN in the alpha anomer and UP in the beta anomer (relative to the ring as conventionally drawn)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "METAL REACTIVITY vs NONMETAL REACTIVITY (opposite corners)", "b": "METAL reactivity = eagerness to LOSE electrons; tracks LOW ionization energy; increases DOWN and LEFT; peaks at the alkali metals (bottom-left). NONMETAL reactivity = eagerness to GAIN electrons; tracks HIGH electronegativity/affinity; increases UP and RIGHT; peaks at fluorine (top-right)."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "WHAT DIFFERS BETWEEN ENANTIOMERS vs WHAT DOES NOT", "b": "DIFFERS: (1) the direction in which they rotate plane-polarized light (equal magnitude, opposite sign); (2) their behavior toward other chiral things, enzymes, receptors, chiral reagents, chiral solvents."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "The First Question To Ask Every Force Problem", "b": "Is the object ACCELERATING or not? If NOT (at rest or constant velocity), the net force is ZERO (equilibrium): forces balance along each axis. If YES, the net force equals ma and points along the acceleration. This single fork, equilibrium versus dynamics, organizes almost every problem."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "ALGORITHM vs HEURISTIC", "b": "ALGORITHM: a step-by-step procedure guaranteed to produce the correct solution if applied correctly. Slow, exhaustive, reliable. Example: a differential diagnosis checklist that works through every criterion in a specified order."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "OUTER MITOCHONDRIAL MEMBRANE vs INNER MITOCHONDRIAL MEMBRANE", "b": "OUTER MEMBRANE contains VDACs (porins); freely permeable to molecules under ~5,000 Da; site of VDAC-mediated release of cytochrome c in apoptosis. INNER MEMBRANE contains all five ETC complexes and ATP synthase; highly impermeable to ions (especially H+); enriched in cardiolipin; folded into cristae…"}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "THE 'BENIGN' vs 'SEVERE' PAIRS", "b": "For BOTH galactose and fructose, the FIRST enzyme (a kinase) causes a MILD/benign condition, while the SECOND enzyme causes the SEVERE one. Galactose: galactokinase deficiency is mild (cataracts only); GALT deficiency (classic galactosemia) is severe."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "FIRST-ROW ANOMALY vs DIAGONAL RELATIONSHIP", "b": "FIRST-ROW ANOMALY: the top element of a group (Li, Be, B, C, N, O, F) behaves differently from the rest of its family because it is very small, has high charge density, and lacks accessible d orbitals (so it cannot exceed an octet and favors strong multiple bonds)."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "R/S vs +/- (THE SIGN OF ROTATION)", "b": "R and S are CONFIGURATIONAL labels assigned by the CIP rules from the spatial arrangement of groups. Plus (dextrorotatory, d) and minus (levorotatory, l) describe the EXPERIMENTAL direction in which the compound rotates plane-polarized light."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "WHAT COUNTS AS WORK vs WHAT DOES NOT", "b": "WORK is done only when a force has a component ALONG the displacement. No displacement means no work, however large the force (holding a weight still). A force perpendicular to the motion does no work (carrying a tray level; the normal force on a sliding block; any centripetal force)."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "REPRESENTATIVENESS vs AVAILABILITY HEURISTIC", "b": "REPRESENTATIVENESS HEURISTIC: judges probability by similarity to a prototype or typical example. Error mode: base rate neglect — ignores how common the category actually is."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "COMPLEX I vs COMPLEX II - WHY FADH2 MAKES LESS ATP THAN NADH", "b": "Both Complex I and Complex II deliver electrons to coenzyme Q. The difference is that Complex I pumps 4 H+ per 2 electrons (a major contribution to the proton-motive force), while Complex II pumps 0 H+."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "SATURATED vs UNSATURATED vs TRANS", "b": "SATURATED: no double bonds, straight tail, packs tightly, SOLID (animal fat). UNSATURATED (cis): double bond(s) create kinks, cannot pack, LIQUID (plant oil)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "THE OCTET AS CAUSE vs CONSEQUENCE", "b": "WRONG framing: atoms bond because they want to complete an octet. RIGHT framing: atoms bond because it lowers the system's potential energy, and for most main-group atoms the energy minimum happens to coincide with eight valence electrons."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "OBSERVED ROTATION vs SPECIFIC ROTATION", "b": "OBSERVED rotation is the raw angle your instrument reads; it depends on concentration and path length and on the particular sample. SPECIFIC rotation is the standardized, intrinsic constant of the compound, obtained by dividing observed rotation by concentration and path length at a fixed temperatur…"}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "KINETIC vs POTENTIAL ENERGY", "b": "2 KINETIC energy is energy of MOTION (KE = 1/2 mv ); it exists whenever something moves and depends on the square of speed. POTENTIAL energy is stored energy of POSITION or CONFIGURATION: gravitational (mgh, depends on height) or elastic (1/2 kx2, stored in a deformation)."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "SYSTEM 1 vs SYSTEM 2 THINKING", "b": "SYSTEM 1: fast, automatic, unconscious, intuitive, heuristic-driven, low effort, always running. Produces pattern recognition, gut feelings, and fast judgments. Source of most cognitive biases. SYSTEM 2: slow, deliberate, conscious, analytical, rule-governed, high effort, activated when needed."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "MALATE-ASPARTATE SHUTTLE vs GLYCEROL-3-PHOSPHATE SHUTTLE", "b": "MALATE-ASPARTATE SHUTTLE: cytoplasm NADH → matrix NADH (same electron carrier); yields ~2.5 ATP per cytoplasmic NADH; operates in liver, heart, and kidney (high aerobic tissues); requires mitochondrial matrix entry of malate and alpha-KG, and cytoplasmic AST and MDH."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "RANKING FLUIDITY (the three-step rule)", "b": "More fluid / lower melting point comes from: (1) MORE double bonds, (2) CIS geometry (kinks), and (3) SHORTER chains. Less fluid / higher melting point: fewer/no double bonds, trans or saturated (straight), and longer chains. Trans is the trap, it is unsaturated by name but packs like saturated."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "LATTICE ENERGY vs MELTING POINT vs HYDRATION ENERGY", "b": "LATTICE ENERGY is the energy released forming the solid lattice from gaseous ions; it tracks charge (dominant) then inverse size. MELTING POINT correlates with lattice energy because both reflect how hard the ions are held."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "ENANTIOMERS vs DIASTEREOMERS", "b": "ENANTIOMERS are mirror images and differ at EVERY stereocenter; they share all ordinary physical properties and cannot be separated by ordinary means. DIASTEREOMERS are not mirror images and differ at SOME BUT NOT ALL stereocenters (or differ by ring/double-bond geometry); they have DIFFERENT physic…"}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "WORK-ENERGY THEOREM vs KINEMATICS", "b": "The KINEMATIC equations (Chapter 1) track motion through TIME and need acceleration. The WORK-ENERGY theorem tracks motion through DISTANCE and needs only forces and displacement, never time."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "STRONG vs WEAK VERSION OF THE SAPIR-WHORF HYPOTHESIS", "b": "STRONG VERSION (linguistic determinism): language determines thought; you cannot think thoughts for which your language has no words. Empirically rejected: speakers of all languages can represent and reason about concepts regardless of whether their language marks those concepts grammatically."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "MODERN (30 - 32 ATP) vs CLASSIC (36 - 38 ATP) YIELDS", "b": "The classic textbook yield of 36 - 38 ATP per glucose was calculated using P:O ratios of 3 ATP per NADH and 2 ATP per FADH2, derived from theoretical considerations."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "What Makes A Membrane More Fluid", "b": "MORE fluid: more UNSATURATED (cis, kinked) fatty-acid tails, shorter tails, and higher temperature. LESS fluid: more SATURATED (straight) tails, longer tails, and lower temperature."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "SIGMA vs PI BONDS", "b": "SIGMA: head-on (end-to-end) orbital overlap along the internuclear axis; the FIRST bond between any two atoms is always sigma; allows free rotation; relatively strong."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "MESO COMPOUND vs PAIR OF ENANTIOMERS", "b": "A MESO compound is ONE achiral molecule containing stereocenters that cancel through an internal mirror plane; it is optically inactive and identical to its own mirror image. A PAIR OF ENANTIOMERS is TWO different chiral molecules that are mirror images of each other; each is optically active."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "CONSERVATIVE vs NONCONSERVATIVE FORCES", "b": "A CONSERVATIVE force (gravity, ideal spring) does work that depends only on start and end points, not the path; it stores energy reversibly and the round-trip work is zero. With only conservative forces, mechanical energy KE + PE is conserved."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "FLUID vs CRYSTALLIZED INTELLIGENCE", "b": "FLUID INTELLIGENCE (Gf): the ability to reason through novel problems, identify patterns, and solve abstract challenges that cannot be resolved by drawing on previously learned knowledge. It is the reasoning capacity itself, independent of content."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "SUBSTRATE-LEVEL PHOSPHORYLATION vs OXIDATIVE PHOSPHORYLATION", "b": "SUBSTRATE-LEVEL PHOSPHORYLATION: direct transfer of phosphate from a high-energy intermediate (1,3-BPG, PEP, succinyl-CoA) to ADP; occurs in glycolysis and TCA cycle; does not require O , membrane 2 potential, or the ETC; 4 reactions total (2 glycolytic + 1 TCA per turn × 2 turns); yields 4 ATP tota…"}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "LDL vs HDL", "b": "LDL delivers cholesterol TO tissues; it is the 'bad' one because high LDL drives plaque and atherosclerosis. HDL carries cholesterol FROM tissues back to the liver (reverse transport); it is the 'good' one because high HDL is protective."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "NONPOLAR COVALENT vs POLAR COVALENT vs IONIC", "b": "NONPOLAR COVALENT: equal sharing, EN difference near zero (identical atoms, or C-H). POLAR COVALENT: unequal sharing, partial charges, a bond dipole, intermediate EN difference. IONIC: complete transfer, full charges, large EN difference."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "2^n AS A MAXIMUM vs THE ACTUAL COUNT", "b": "2^n gives the MAXIMUM number of stereoisomers for n stereocenters, and it is exactly right for molecules with no internal symmetry. The ACTUAL count is LESS than 2^n whenever the molecule has internal symmetry that creates meso forms or makes two predicted structures identical."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "ELASTIC vs INELASTIC ENERGY CONSERVATION", "b": "ELASTIC potential energy (springs, tendons, rubber) IS conserved: energy stored in a deformed spring is fully returned when the spring rebounds, because the spring force is conservative."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "RELIABILITY vs VALIDITY", "b": "RELIABILITY refers to the consistency of a test: does it produce the same results on repeated administration (test-retest reliability), across different raters scoring the same performance (inter-rater reliability), and across different items that are supposed to measure the same thing (internal con…"}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "The Four 'Increases O2 Consumption' Conditions To Keep Straight", "b": "Four distinct conditions increase O2 consumption, but for different reasons: (1) UNCOUPLERS (2,4-DNP, UCP1, salicylate): collapse the proton gradient; ETC accelerates to try to rebuild it; O consumption rises; ATP 2 synthesis stops; heat produced."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "The Full Lipoprotein Cascade In Order", "b": "Chylomicrons carry DIETARY fat from the gut. The liver then exports its own fat as VLDL. As VLDL drops off triglyceride to tissues it shrinks and becomes LDL, which delivers cholesterol to tissues (and into artery walls when high)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "FORMAL CHARGE vs OXIDATION NUMBER", "b": "FORMAL CHARGE assumes bonding electrons are split EVENLY (half to each atom) and asks how an atom's electron count differs from its neutral valence; it picks the best Lewis structure."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "ABSOLUTE vs RELATIVE CONFIGURATION", "b": "ABSOLUTE configuration is the true spatial arrangement at a stereocenter, named R or S, identifying exactly which enantiomer is present. RELATIVE configuration describes the relationship between stereocenters (or to a reference), such as cis/trans or syn/anti, without necessarily fixing the absolute…"}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "WORK vs POWER vs ENERGY", "b": "ENERGY and WORK are amounts, measured in joules; they answer how much. POWER is a rate, measured in watts (joules per second); it answers how fast. Two people who climb the same stairs do the same work and spend the same energy, but the one who runs up produces more power."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "DIVERGENT vs CONVERGENT THINKING", "b": "DIVERGENT THINKING: generating multiple possible solutions, associations, or perspectives from a single starting point. The cognitive mode of creativity, brainstorming, and open-ended exploration."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "GLUCOGENIC vs KETOGENIC AMINO ACIDS", "b": "A glucogenic amino acid can provide carbon for glucose synthesis because its degradation yields a TCA cycle intermediate or pyruvate, both of which can be converted to oxaloacetate (OAA) and then to phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP), entering gluconeogenesis."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "Interpreting The Panel At A Glance", "b": "HIGH LDL = bad (more cholesterol to arteries) -> raises risk. LOW HDL = bad (less cleanup) -> raises risk. HIGH HDL = good (protective). HIGH triglycerides = more VLDL/chylomicron, raises risk. The worst combination is high LDL with low HDL."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "RESONANCE vs EQUILIBRIUM (a classic trap)", "b": "RESONANCE structures are different DRAWINGS of ONE molecule; the molecule is a single hybrid and nothing is actually moving or interconverting (double-headed arrow). EQUILIBRIUM is two DIFFERENT molecules genuinely interconverting (forward/back arrows)."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "CONFIGURATIONAL vs CONFORMATIONAL ISOMERS", "b": "CONFIGURATIONAL isomers (enantiomers, diastereomers, cis/trans) interconvert ONLY by BREAKING BONDS; they are distinct, isolable compounds. CONFORMATIONAL isomers (conformers: staggered/eclipsed, chair/boat) interconvert by ROTATION about single bonds, with NO bond breaking; they are the same compou…"}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "MOMENTUM vs KINETIC ENERGY", "b": "MOMENTUM (p = mv) is a VECTOR: it has direction, can be positive or negative, and the momenta of a system add as vectors and can cancel. It scales LINEARLY with speed. KINETIC ENERGY (1/2 mv2) is a SCALAR: it has no direction, is never negative, and always adds. It scales with the SQUARE of speed."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "FREUDIAN vs COGNITIVE UNCONSCIOUS", "b": "FREUDIAN UNCONSCIOUS: material actively excluded from awareness by defense mechanisms; contains drives, repressed memories, and wishes; revealed through dreams, parapraxes (Freudian slips), and free association; a dynamic, motivated system."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "F-2,6-BP vs F-1,6-BP", "b": "Fructose-2,6-bisphosphate (F-2,6-BP) and fructose-1,6-bisphosphate (F-1,6-BP) are structurally similar but functionally completely different. F-1,6-BP is a glycolytic INTERMEDIATE - it is the product of PFK-1, and it is split by aldolase into DHAP and G-3-P."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "NUCLEOSIDE vs NUCLEOTIDE", "b": "NUCLEOSIDE = sugar + base (no phosphate). NUCLEOTIDE = sugar + base + phosphate(s). The phosphate is the only difference. Memory hook: nucleoTide = phosphaTe (both have a T)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "Who Can Expand The Octet", "b": "CAN expand (period 3 and below, empty d orbitals available): P, S, Cl, Br, I, Xe, and friends, giving species like PCl5, SF6, ICl4-, XeF4. CANNOT expand (period 2, no d subshell): C, N, O, F, ever. If a proposed structure puts more than eight electrons on a second-row atom, it is wrong, full stop."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "SATURATED vs UNSATURATED", "b": "SATURATED (alkane): only single bonds, formula CnH2n+2, maximum hydrogens, no degrees of unsaturation, generally unreactive toward the polar reagents of earlier chapters."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "WORK vs IMPULSE", "b": "Both WORK and IMPULSE involve a force, but they differ in what that force acts through. WORK is force times DISPLACEMENT (W = Fd cos θ): it measures how much energy a force transfers and changes KINETIC ENERGY."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Eeg Signatures Of Sleep Stages", "b": "AWAKE (alert): beta waves, 13-30 Hz, low amplitude, desynchronized. AWAKE (relaxed, eyes closed): alpha waves, 8-12 Hz, medium amplitude, posterior. N1 (drowsy): theta waves, 4-7 Hz; hypnic jerks possible; brief, easily awakened."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "GLYCOGEN PHOSPHORYLASE vs DEBRANCHING ENZYME PRODUCTS", "b": "GLYCOGEN PHOSPHORYLASE produces GLUCOSE-1-PHOSPHATE by phosphorolysis of alpha-1,4 bonds. The phosphate group comes from inorganic Pi, not from ATP. The glucose-1-phosphate bypasses hexokinase in glycolysis, saving one ATP."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "AMP vs ADP vs ATP (and why polymerases use triphosphates)", "b": "AMP = one phosphate, ADP = two, ATP = three. More phosphates = more stored energy in the phosphoanhydride bonds. Nucleic-acid synthesis uses nucleoside TRIPHOSPHATES as substrates: the polymerase cleaves off pyrophosphate (two phosphates), and that energy release drives the phosphodiester bond forma…"}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "ELECTRON GEOMETRY vs MOLECULAR SHAPE", "b": "ELECTRON GEOMETRY counts ALL domains (bonds plus lone pairs) and names how they arrange. MOLECULAR SHAPE names only where the ATOMS are, ignoring lone pairs. They match when there are no lone pairs."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "CHAIN LENGTH vs BRANCHING ON BOILING POINT", "b": "CHAIN LENGTH: comparing different formulas, more carbons means a higher boiling point, because total dispersion surface increases. BRANCHING: comparing the SAME formula (isomers), more branching means a LOWER boiling point, because the compact shape exposes less surface."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "ELASTIC vs INELASTIC vs PERFECTLY INELASTIC", "b": "ALL collisions conserve MOMENTUM (if external forces are negligible). They differ only in KINETIC ENERGY. ELASTIC: kinetic energy is also conserved; objects bounce apart cleanly (billiard balls, atoms)."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Nrem-Rem Timing Across The Night", "b": "EARLY NIGHT (first two cycles): dominated by N3 slow-wave sleep; REM episodes are brief (5-10 min); growth hormone peaks here; declarative memory consolidation (hippocampal-cortical transfer) is active."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "NADPH vs NADH - NOT INTERCHANGEABLE", "b": "NADH is produced by glycolysis, the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex, and the TCA cycle. Its electrons are fed into Complex I of the electron transport chain to drive ATP synthesis. NADH's role is CATABOLIC energy transduction."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "5' END vs 3' END (and why polymerases care)", "b": "The 5' end has a free PHOSPHATE on the 5' carbon; the 3' end has a free HYDROXYL on the 3' carbon. Sequences are written 5'->3'. Every DNA and RNA polymerase adds nucleotides ONLY to the 3' end, so synthesis always runs 5'->3'."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "POLAR BOND vs POLAR MOLECULE", "b": "A POLAR BOND is a single bond with unequal electron sharing (a bond dipole). A POLAR MOLECULE has a NET dipole after summing all bond dipoles as vectors. A molecule can have polar bonds yet be nonpolar if symmetry cancels them (CO2, CCl4, SF6)."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "RADICAL (and CARBOCATION) STABILITY ORDER", "b": "Most stable to least stable: TERTIARY > SECONDARY > PRIMARY > METHYL. The reason is the same for radicals and carbocations: both are electron-deficient carbons stabilized by adjacent alkyl groups through hyperconjugation and inductive donation."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "CENTER OF MASS vs CENTER OF GRAVITY", "b": "The CENTER OF MASS is the mass-weighted average position of a body, a purely geometric and mass property. The CENTER OF GRAVITY is the point where gravity effectively acts."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "OBSTRUCTIVE vs CENTRAL SLEEP APNEA", "b": "OBSTRUCTIVE SLEEP APNEA (OSA): caused by physical collapse of the upper airway; respiratory effort continues (chest and abdominal movement is present) but airflow stops; associated with obesity, large neck circumference, retrognathia, male sex; loud snoring is characteristic; treated with CPAP, whic…"}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "McARDLE DISEASE (TYPE V) vs TARUI DISEASE (TYPE VII)", "b": "Both: exercise intolerance, painful cramps, myoglobinuria, no lactate rise on ischemic forearm exercise, glycogen accumulation in muscle. DISTINGUISHING FEATURE: Tarui disease (PFK-1 deficiency) also causes HEMOLYTIC ANEMIA because red blood cells also express PFK-1 and also lack it."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "The Base Pairs And Their Bond Counts", "b": "A pairs with T using TWO hydrogen bonds. G pairs with C using THREE hydrogen bonds. Always purine + pyrimidine. Consequence: DNA rich in G-C is held together more tightly and takes more energy (higher temperature) to separate."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "Counting Domains For Hybridization", "b": "Hybridization is set ONLY by the number of electron domains (σ bonds + lone pairs), NOT by the number of atoms or the bond order. A double or triple bond is ONE domain."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "CONFORMATION vs CONFIGURATION (ISOMER)", "b": "CONFORMATIONS interconvert by rotation about single bonds alone, with no bonds broken; they are the SAME molecule in different shapes and cannot be separated."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "DENSITY vs SPECIFIC GRAVITY", "b": "3 3 DENSITY is mass per volume and carries units (kg/m or g/cm ); it is an absolute property. SPECIFIC GRAVITY is the ratio of that density to water's density and is DIMENSIONLESS (no units)."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Mechanisms Of Major Psychoactive Drugs", "b": "DEPRESSANTS: Alcohol: GABA-A positive modulator (increased Cl- channel frequency) + NMDA antagonist. Benzodiazepines: GABA-A positive modulator (increased frequency; requires GABA to act). Barbiturates: GABA-A positive modulator (increased duration; can open channel WITHOUT GABA at high doses)."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "VON GIERKE (TYPE I) vs CORI DISEASE (TYPE III)", "b": "Both: hepatomegaly, fasting hypoglycemia, glycogen accumulation in liver. DIFFERENCES: Von Gierke: G6Pase deficiency; BOTH glycogenolysis AND GNG produce G-6-P that is trapped; glucagon does NOT raise glucose; severe lactic acidosis; hyperlipidemia; hyperuricemia from G-6-P → PPP overflow."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "WATSON-CRICK PAIRING vs WOBBLE vs TAUTOMER MISPAIRING", "b": "Watson-Crick pairing: the standard A-T and G-C pairs that build the stable helix. Wobble: a relaxed, NORMAL pairing allowed at the third codon position so one tRNA reads several codons (explains code degeneracy and silent mutations)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "BONDING vs ANTIBONDING ORBITALS", "b": "BONDING orbital: atomic orbitals combine IN PHASE; electron density builds up BETWEEN the nuclei; LOWER energy; stabilizes the bond. ANTIBONDING orbital (marked with a star): combine OUT OF PHASE; a NODE forms between the nuclei; HIGHER energy; destabilizes the bond."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "TORSIONAL STRAIN vs STERIC STRAIN", "b": "TORSIONAL (eclipsing) strain comes from bonds lining up (eclipsed, 0 degree dihedral); it exists even between tiny atoms like the hydrogens of ethane, because it is about bond-bond alignment, not size."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "GAUGE vs ABSOLUTE PRESSURE", "b": "GAUGE pressure is pressure measured RELATIVE to the surrounding atmosphere; it is the ρ*g*h term, what a cuff or tire gauge reads, and it can read zero (or even negative) while real air remains inside. ABSOLUTE pressure is the TOTAL pressure including atmosphere: P_absolute = P_atm + P_gauge."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "TOLERANCE vs DEPENDENCE vs ADDICTION", "b": "TOLERANCE: reduced pharmacological response to repeated drug exposure; requires dose escalation to maintain effect. Mechanism: receptor down-regulation, uncoupling, or metabolic induction. CAN occur without dependence or addiction."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "POMPE (TYPE II) vs ALL OTHER GSDs", "b": "Pompe disease is the ONLY GSD with LYSOSOMAL glycogen accumulation. All other GSDs involve CYTOPLASMIC or CYTOSKELETAL glycogen, defects in cytoplasmic enzymes of glycogen metabolism, or mitochondria-adjacent events."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "DNA vs RNA (the four differences)", "b": "Sugar: DNA = deoxyribose, RNA = ribose. Base: DNA = thymine, RNA = uracil. Strands: DNA = double, RNA = single (usually). Role: DNA stores, RNA expresses."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "Ranking Imf And Predicting Boiling Point", "b": "To compare boiling points: first ask if hydrogen bonding is possible (H on N/O/F) - if one substance H-bonds and another does not, the H-bonder usually boils higher. If neither H-bonds, compare dipole-dipole (polar beats nonpolar)."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "ANTI vs GAUCHE", "b": "ANTI: the two large groups are 180 degrees apart (opposite sides), staggered, no steric crowding; this is the global energy MINIMUM and the most populated conformation. GAUCHE: the two large groups are 60 degrees apart, still staggered but crowded; a LOCAL minimum a few kJ/mol above anti."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "FORCE MULTIPLICATION vs ENERGY 'GAIN'", "b": "Hydraulics multiply FORCE (a small input force yields a large output force, by the area ratio) but never create ENERGY. Because the incompressible fluid moves equal volumes on both sides, the small piston travels a proportionally larger distance, so work in equals work out (ignoring friction)."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "YERKES-DODSON: EASY vs COMPLEX TASKS", "b": "The Yerkes-Dodson law produces an INVERTED U: arousal on the x-axis, performance on the y-axis, peak in the middle. The CRITICAL DISTINCTION is where the peak sits."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "CIS vs TRANS FATTY ACIDS: EFFECTS ON PLASMA LIPIDS", "b": "CIS unsaturated FA: lower LDL (they displace saturated FA and reduce hepatic cholesterol synthesis signaling), modestly raise or maintain HDL. NET: favorable cardiovascular profile."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "WHO PROVED WHAT (don't mix these up)", "b": "Griffith = transformation EXISTS (unknown principle). Avery = the principle IS DNA. Hershey-Chase = DNA (not protein) is the genetic material (radioactive phage experiment). Meselson-Stahl = replication is SEMICONSERVATIVE (heavy/light nitrogen)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "The Four Bonding Models At A Glance", "b": "IONIC: electron transfer; metal + nonmetal; lattice of ions; hard, brittle, high-melting, conducts only when molten/dissolved. COVALENT: electron sharing; nonmetal + nonmetal; discrete molecules; properties set by intermolecular forces."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "AXIAL vs EQUATORIAL (and what the ring flip does)", "b": "AXIAL: points straight up or down, parallel to the ring axis, alternating around the ring; a crowded position. EQUATORIAL: points outward around the ring's equator; a roomy position."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "Which Density And Which Volume In Buoyancy", "b": "BUOYANT FORCE uses the FLUID's density and the DISPLACED (submerged) volume: F_b = rho_fluid x V_displaced x g. The OBJECT's WEIGHT uses the OBJECT's density and its FULL volume: W = rho_object x V_object x g. The classic error is plugging the object's density into the buoyant force."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Overjustification Effect", "b": "The OVERJUSTIFICATION EFFECT occurs when an EXTERNAL REWARD is introduced for a behavior driven by INTRINSIC MOTIVATION. The person comes to attribute their engagement to the reward rather than to internal interest; when the reward is removed, motivation drops BELOW its original baseline."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "PRIMARY CARNITINE DEFICIENCY vs MCAD DEFICIENCY", "b": "Both present with hypoketotic hypoglycemia during fasting but differ in mechanism. PRIMARY CARNITINE DEFICIENCY: mutation in the carnitine transporter (OCTN2) → cannot import carnitine into cells → cannot form acylcarnitine → ALL long-chain FA blocked from entering mitochondria → additionally, free…"}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "CODON vs ANTICODON, EXON vs INTRON", "b": "A CODON is the three-base unit on the mRNA that specifies an amino acid; the ANTICODON is the complementary three-base unit on the tRNA that reads it. EXONs are the coding pieces that stay in the mature mRNA (EXons are EXpressed); INTRONs are the non-coding pieces spliced OUT (INTrons stay IN the nu…"}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "MOLAR MASS vs MOLECULAR MASS vs MOLAR QUANTITY", "b": "MOLAR MASS is mass per mole, grams per mole, a property of the substance read off the periodic table. MOLECULAR (or formula) MASS is the same number expressed for a single molecule in atomic mass units, so water is 18.02 amu per molecule and 18.02 g/mol per mole, numerically identical, different uni…"}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "cis/trans (CONFIGURATION) vs WHICH-CHAIR (CONFORMATION)", "b": "cis/trans is CONFIGURATION: a fixed relationship (same face vs opposite faces) that the ring flip CANNOT change; cis and trans are separable, different compounds."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "COHESION vs ADHESION", "b": "COHESION is attraction between LIKE molecules of the same liquid (water to water); it produces surface tension and a convex meniscus when it dominates (mercury)."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "ORGANIZATIONAL vs ACTIVATIONAL HORMONE EFFECTS", "b": "ORGANIZATIONAL effects: occur during a CRITICAL DEVELOPMENTAL PERIOD (prenatal / early postnatal); PERMANENTLY structure neural circuits; cannot be reversed by changing adult hormone levels."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "MITOCHONDRIAL HMG-CoA vs CYTOPLASMIC HMG-CoA", "b": "HMG-CoA appears in TWO pathways and TWO compartments: (1) MITOCHONDRIAL HMG-CoA: formed by mitochondrial HMG-CoA SYNTHASE from acetoacetyl-CoA + acetyl-CoA; cleaved by HMG-CoA LYASE to give acetoacetate (KETOGENESIS)."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "DNA VIRUSES vs RNA VIRUSES vs RETROVIRUSES", "b": "DNA viruses: carry DNA, generally replicate in the host NUCLEUS using DNA machinery, mutate slowly. RNA viruses: carry RNA, usually replicate in the CYTOPLASM with a viral RNA-dependent RNA polymerase, mutate FAST (poor proofreading)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "EMPIRICAL vs MOLECULAR FORMULA", "b": "EMPIRICAL is the smallest whole-number RATIO of atoms (CH2O); it comes straight from percent composition and tells you nothing about the molecule's size. MOLECULAR is the ACTUAL count per molecule (C H O ); getting it requires one extra piece of data, the molar mass, to find the multiplier."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "NUCLEOPHILICITY vs BASICITY", "b": "These two are constantly confused because both describe electron-pair donation, but they measure different things. BASICITY is thermodynamic: how favorably a species grabs a PROTON (H+), measured by the pKa of its conjugate acid. NUCLEOPHILICITY is kinetic: how FAST a species attacks a CARBON."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "FLOW RATE (Q) vs FLOW SPEED (v)", "b": "VOLUME FLOW RATE Q = A x v (units m3/s) is CONSTANT along a closed pipe by conservation of mass; it is the same everywhere. FLOW SPEED v (units m/s) is NOT constant; it rises in narrow sections and falls in wide ones so that Q stays fixed."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "JAMES-LANGE vs CANNON-BARD THEORIES", "b": "JAMES-LANGE: stimulus → physiological response → perceived body state = emotion. Emotion IS the brain's perception of peripheral bodily changes. Each emotion has a distinct physiological pattern."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "FA SYNTHESIS vs BETA-OXIDATION: RECIPROCAL REGULATION", "b": "The same hormonal signal that activates FA synthesis inhibits β-oxidation, and vice versa. INSULIN (fed state): activates ACC (dephosphorylation) → malonyl-CoA rises → CAT I inhibited → FA cannot enter mitochondria for oxidation. Simultaneously, insulin inhibits HSL (blocks lipolysis)."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "The Four Nucleotide Disorders, Sorted", "b": "Purine PROBLEMS: Lesch-Nyhan (absent HGPRT salvage -> high uric acid, neuro signs) and gout (uric acid crystals in joints). Purine + immune: ADA deficiency -> SCID. Pyrimidine problem: hereditary orotic aciduria (cannot make UMP -> orotic acid in urine, megaloblastic anemia)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "COEFFICIENT vs SUBSCRIPT", "b": "A COEFFICIENT (the number in front, like the 2 in 2 H2O) multiplies the whole formula and tells you HOW MANY molecules; changing it is legal and is how you balance."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "Protic Favors Sn1/E1, Aprotic Favors Sn2", "b": "PROTIC solvent (has O-H/N-H) stabilizes ions, including the carbocation intermediate and the departing leaving group, so it speeds the ionization step that begins SN1 and E1. It also cages and weakens the nucleophile, which suppresses SN2."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "CONTINUITY vs BERNOULLI (they work as a pair)", "b": "CONTINUITY (A1*v1 = A2*v2) is conservation of MASS and tells you the SPEED: narrow means fast. BERNOULLI (P + 1/2 rho v2 +ρ g h = const) is conservation of ENERGY and tells you the PRESSURE: fast means low pressure."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "SAM AXIS vs HPA AXIS", "b": "SAM AXIS: FAST (seconds); mediators = EPINEPHRINE and NOREPINEPHRINE from adrenal MEDULLA; driven by SYMPATHETIC nervous system; effects = immediate fight-or-flight (heart rate up, bronchodilation, glucose mobilized, blood to muscles); RESOLVES QUICKLY when stressor ends."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "ApoB-48 vs ApoB-100", "b": "ApoB-48: made ONLY in intestinal enterocytes; present ONLY in chylomicrons (and remnants). Result of RNA editing that creates a premature stop codon. Lacks the LDL-receptor binding domain - so chylomicrons CANNOT be cleared by LDL receptors."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "THE MAJOR DNA-REPAIR PATHWAYS (and their diseases)", "b": "Mismatch repair fixes wrong bases the polymerase missed; its failure causes Lynch syndrome (hereditary colon cancer). Nucleotide excision repair removes bulky lesions like UV thymine dimers; its failure causes xeroderma pigmentosum."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "OXIDIZING AGENT vs REDUCING AGENT", "b": "The OXIDIZING AGENT is the species that CAUSES oxidation in its partner by accepting electrons, so it is itself REDUCED. The REDUCING AGENT causes reduction by donating electrons, so it is itself OXIDIZED."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "Sn2 At A Glance", "b": "ONE step (concerted), no intermediate. RATE = k[substrate][nucleophile], second-order. STEREOCHEMISTRY: inversion of configuration (Walden inversion) - one enantiomer in, the inverted enantiomer out. SUBSTRATE: methyl > 1 > 2 >> 3 (tertiary does not react; backside blocked)."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "LAMINAR vs TURBULENT FLOW", "b": "LAMINAR flow is smooth, layered, silent, and predicted by a LOW Reynolds number (viscosity wins); it is the normal, efficient regime for blood in healthy vessels."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "PROBLEM-FOCUSED vs EMOTION-FOCUSED COPING", "b": "PROBLEM-FOCUSED coping: addresses the STRESSOR ITSELF by changing the situation; most adaptive when the stressor is CONTROLLABLE (e.g., studying more for an upcoming exam, negotiating a deadline, learning a skill)."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "COX-1 vs COX-2 and Drug Selectivity", "b": "COX-1 (constitutive): housekeeping prostaglandins. Inhibition → loss of gastric mucosal protection (ulcers, GI bleeding), loss of platelet TXA2 (impaired hemostasis). COX-2 (inducible): inflammatory prostaglandins."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "LIGHT vs ELECTRON MICROSCOPY", "b": "LIGHT microscopy: uses light, lower resolution (~200 nm limit), CAN view LIVING cells and color, sees cells and big organelles. ELECTRON microscopy: uses electrons, far HIGHER resolution (sees individual organelles, membranes, macromolecules), but only DEAD/fixed samples (vacuum)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "SPECTATOR ION vs PARTICIPATING ION", "b": "A SPECTATOR ION appears in identical form on both sides of the complete ionic equation, fully dissolved before and after; it does not change and is cancelled to reach the net ionic equation."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "SN1 vs SN2 (the single most tested distinction in the chapter)", "b": "SN1: TWO steps, carbocation intermediate, rate = k[substrate] (first-order, nucleophile absent from rate law), RACEMIZATION (flat cation, both faces), substrate 3 > 2 >> 1 (needs a stable cation), favored by WEAK nucleophile + PROTIC solvent."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "CONTINUITY's v vs POISEUILLE's Q (don't mix the radius logic)", "b": "CONTINUITY (ideal fluid, conservation of mass): in a single continuous pipe a narrowing SPEEDS UP the fluid (v goes as 1/r2) but the volume flow rate Q is unchanged."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "CRITICAL PERIOD vs SENSITIVE PERIOD", "b": "A CRITICAL PERIOD is a narrow, obligatory window: the relevant experience MUST occur within it for normal development. Absence of the experience produces permanent impairment even if the experience arrives later."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "TYPE I vs TYPE IIA vs TYPE IV HYPERLIPOPROTEINEMIA", "b": "These three Fredrickson types cover the most commonly tested scenarios in clinical vignettes. TYPE I (LPL or ApoC-II deficiency): elevated CHYLOMICRONS. Triglycerides >1000 mg/dL. Plasma creamy layer on top, clear infranatant. Pancreatitis risk (severe). Eruptive xanthomas."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "SURFACE AREA vs VOLUME AS A CELL GROWS", "b": "As radius increases, SURFACE AREA grows with r-squared but VOLUME grows with r-cubed, so the surface-area-to-volume RATIO falls. Smaller cells have a HIGHER ratio (more membrane per unit contents) and exchange material efficiently; very large cells cannot supply their interior."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "LIMITING vs EXCESS REAGENT", "b": "The LIMITING reagent runs out first and sets the maximum product; it is fully consumed. The EXCESS reagent is whatever is left over after the limiting reagent is gone."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "REARRANGEMENT MEANS CARBOCATION (SN1/E1, never SN2/E2)", "b": "A hydride or methyl shift can only happen if there is a carbocation for a group to migrate TO. Concerted reactions (SN2, E2) have no carbocation intermediate, so they CANNOT rearrange and always give a product with the carbon skeleton intact."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "The Four Questions That Decide A Fluids Problem", "b": "(1) Is the fluid at rest or moving? At rest → P = ρ*g*h. (2) Floating/sinking? → compare densities, fraction submerged = rho_obj/rho_fluid. (3) Moving through a size change? → continuity for speed, then Bernoulli for pressure (faster = lower P)."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "CROSS-SECTIONAL vs LONGITUDINAL RESEARCH DESIGN", "b": "CROSS-SECTIONAL: Tests multiple age groups simultaneously. FAST and CHEAP. Confound: COHORT EFFECTS — groups differ in age AND in historical generation, so differences may reflect era, not aging. Cannot track individual change over time. LONGITUDINAL: Follows the SAME people over time."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "STATINS vs EZETIMIBE vs BILE ACID RESINS vs PCSK9 INHIBITORS", "b": "Each class lowers LDL by a distinct mechanism, and the mechanism predicts both efficacy and side-effect profile. STATINS (atorvastatin, rosuvastatin, simvastatin): inhibit HMG-CoA reductase → reduce hepatic cholesterol synthesis → SREBP activation → upregulate LDL receptor → increase LDL clearance."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "NUCLEUS vs NUCLEOLUS", "b": "The NUCLEUS is the whole membrane-bound compartment holding the DNA. The NUCLEOLUS is a dense sub-region INSIDE the nucleus (not separately membrane-bound) where ribosomal RNA is synthesized and ribosomes are assembled. One houses the genome; the other builds ribosomes."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "THEORETICAL vs ACTUAL vs PERCENT YIELD", "b": "THEORETICAL yield is the calculated maximum from the limiting reagent, the best case if everything went perfectly. ACTUAL yield is the measured amount you really recover, always equal to or less than theoretical."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "E2 At A Glance", "b": "ONE step (concerted), no intermediate. RATE = k[substrate][base], second-order. GEOMETRY: the beta-H and the leaving group must be ANTI-PERIPLANAR (180 degrees); in cyclohexane, both axial. STEREOSPECIFIC: the required anti alignment fixes the alkene geometry."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "CELSIUS vs KELVIN", "b": "SAME SIZE DEGREE: a change of 1 K equals a change of 1 degree C, so temperature DIFFERENCES (deltaT) are numerically identical in either scale, which is why Q = mc*deltaT works fine in Celsius."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "PIAGET vs VYGOTSKY", "b": "PIAGET: Development is driven by the INDIVIDUAL CHILD's active engagement with the physical world. The child constructs knowledge solo through assimilation, accommodation, and equilibration. Cognitive development is UNIVERSAL and follows fixed STAGES tied to biological maturation."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "AST vs ALT: TISSUE SPECIFICITY AND CLINICAL MEANING", "b": "ALT (alanine aminotransferase): found predominantly in HEPATOCYTES. Elevation is a SPECIFIC marker of hepatocellular damage. In viral hepatitis and acetaminophen toxicity, ALT > AST."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "ROUGH ER vs SMOOTH ER", "b": "ROUGH ER: has ribosomes; makes SECRETORY and membrane/organelle proteins; starts N-linked glycosylation. SMOOTH ER: no ribosomes; makes LIPIDS and STEROIDS, detoxifies drugs/poisons, holds glucose-6-phosphatase. Memory hook: Rough = Ribosomes = pRoteins for export; Smooth = Steroids and detox."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "MOLARITY vs MOLALITY vs MOLE FRACTION", "b": "MOLARITY (M) is moles of solute per liter of SOLUTION; it is temperature-dependent because volume expands with heat, and it is what you use for solution stoichiometry and titration."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "E1 vs E2", "b": "E1: TWO steps via a carbocation, rate = k[substrate] (first-order, base absent from rate law), needs a STABLE cation so 3 > 2 (never 1), favored by WEAK base + PROTIC solvent, follows Zaitsev, CAN rearrange, NOT stereospecific, travels with SN1."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "HEAT vs TEMPERATURE vs INTERNAL ENERGY", "b": "INTERNAL ENERGY: total molecular kinetic + potential energy of a substance; a STATE quantity (depends only on current condition); more molecules means more of it. TEMPERATURE: the AVERAGE translational kinetic energy per molecule; an intensive property; sets the DIRECTION of heat flow."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "KOHLBERG'S JUSTICE ORIENTATION vs GILLIGAN'S CARE ORIENTATION", "b": "KOHLBERG (Justice Orientation): Moral reasoning is about RIGHTS, RULES, and IMPARTIALITY. The pinnacle (Stage 6) involves applying universal principles of justice that transcend specific relationships. Developed from an all-male sample. Highest-level reasoning = abstract, detached, principled."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "CPS-I vs CPS-II - THE MOST IMPORTANT TABLE IN CHAPTER 7", "b": "Two enzymes are named carbamoyl phosphate synthetase, and their confusion is one of the most common errors on both the MCAT and Step 1. CPS-I: MITOCHONDRIAL MATRIX. Uses FREE NH4+ as nitrogen source. Requires N-ACETYLGLUTAMATE as obligatory allosteric activator."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "Evidence For The Endosymbiotic Theory", "b": "Mitochondria (and chloroplasts) look like former bacteria because they have: their own CIRCULAR DNA, their own 70S-like RIBOSOMES, a DOUBLE membrane (the inner one from the original bacterium, the outer from the host's engulfing membrane), and they DIVIDE independently by binary fission."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "EQUIVALENCE POINT vs ENDPOINT", "b": "The EQUIVALENCE POINT is the theoretical moment when titrant exactly matches the analyte by the reaction stoichiometry, a fact about moles. The ENDPOINT is the observed signal, an indicator color change, that we use to STOP the titration."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "ZAITSEV vs HOFMANN", "b": "ZAITSEV product = the MORE substituted, more stable alkene = the DEFAULT, formed with small ordinary bases (OH-, EtO-, MeO-) and in E1. The driving force is alkene stability."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "Q = mc*deltaT vs Q = mL", "b": "Q = mc*deltaT applies WITHIN a single phase, when temperature is changing (the sloped parts of a heating curve). Q = mL applies DURING a phase change, when temperature is constant (the flat plateaus)."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Ainsworth'S Four Attachment Types", "b": "SECURE (~65%): Distressed at separation, seeks caregiver at reunion, easily soothed, returns to exploration. Caregiver: consistently SENSITIVE and RESPONSIVE. ANXIOUS-AVOIDANT (~20%): Minimal distress at separation, AVOIDS caregiver at reunion, appears indifferent."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "OTC DEFICIENCY vs CPS-I DEFICIENCY - THE OROTIC ACID KEY", "b": "Both disorders present with severe hyperammonemia, low BUN (urea is not being made), elevated glutamine, and normal or low citrulline. The SINGLE discriminating test is URINARY OROTIC ACID. OTC DEFICIENCY: orotic acid is ELEVATED."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "APOPTOSIS vs NECROSIS", "b": "APOPTOSIS: programmed, controlled, energy-REQUIRING; cell shrinks and is packaged; NO inflammation; normal and often beneficial (development, immune editing, removing pre-cancerous cells)."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "The Four Cues That Decide The Setup", "b": "Mass in, mass out, single reactant → mass-to-mass via the mole bridge. Amounts of TWO reactants → limiting reagent (compare moles/coefficient). Adding or removing solvent → dilution, M1V1 = M2V2. Burette, indicator, equivalence point → titration, M-a V-a equals M-b V-b scaled by the balanced ratio."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "The Four-Way Decision In One Paragraph", "b": "Start with SUBSTRATE: methyl/1 cannot ionize (no SN1/E1); tertiary cannot do SN2 (no backside). Then REAGENT: strong unhindered nucleophile = SN2; strong base, especially bulky = E2; weak nucleophile/base in protic solvent = SN1/E1 mixture."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "THE PHYSICS SIGN CONVENTION (deltaU = Q - W)", "b": "PHYSICS (this book): deltaU = Q - W, where W is the work done BY the system. Q > 0 = heat IN; W > 0 = system EXPANDS / does work on surroundings. So a gas absorbing heat and expanding: Q positive (gains), W positive (spends), net deltaU is the difference."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Marcia'S Four Identity Statuses", "b": "The two dimensions are EXPLORATION (has the person considered alternatives?) and COMMITMENT (has the person made a stable identity choice?). ACHIEVEMENT: Exploration YES + Commitment YES = has explored and committed. Healthiest outcome; authentic, self-constructed identity."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "PDH vs BCKDH - SAME COFACTORS, DIFFERENT SUBSTRATES", "b": "Pyruvate dehydrogenase (PDH) and branched-chain α-keto acid dehydrogenase (BCKDH) are homologous + complexes that share all five cofactors: THIAMINE (B1, as TPP), LIPOIC ACID, FAD (B2), NAD (B3/niacin), and COENZYME A (pantothenic acid)."}, {"s": "Biology", "t": "KINESIN vs DYNEIN (direction matters)", "b": "KINESIN: walks toward the PLUS end of the microtubule = ANTEROGRADE = toward the periphery (away from the nucleus). DYNEIN: walks toward the MINUS end = RETROGRADE = toward the nucleus/center. Memory hook: kinesin = Kicks cargo out (to the periphery); dynein = Drags it back in."}, {"s": "Gen Chem", "t": "Open-Ended Manometer, Which Way To Add", "b": "If the mercury is HIGHER on the open (atmosphere) side, the trapped gas is pushing harder than the atmosphere, so the gas pressure is ABOVE atmospheric: P(gas) = P(atm) + h."}, {"s": "Organic", "t": "The Four Cues That Decide Every Question", "b": "(1) SUBSTRATE: methyl/primary forbids SN1/E1; tertiary forbids SN2; secondary allows all four. (2) REAGENT: strong unhindered nucleophile -> SN2; strong base, especially bulky -> E2; weak nucleophile/base -> SN1/E1. (3) SOLVENT: aprotic confirms SN2, protic confirms SN1/E1."}, {"s": "Physics", "t": "WORK BY THE GAS vs WORK ON THE GAS", "b": "EXPANSION (volume up, path moves RIGHT): gas does POSITIVE work on surroundings (W > 0); area under the path is positive. COMPRESSION (volume down, path moves LEFT): work is done ON the gas (W < 0 in the deltaU = Q - W convention)."}, {"s": "Psych/Soc", "t": "Id, Ego, And Superego: Which Operates On Which Principle", "b": "ID operates on the PLEASURE PRINCIPLE: it seeks immediate drive gratification, uses primary process (illogical, symbolic, wishful) thinking, and has no contact with reality or morality. It is entirely UNCONSCIOUS."}, {"s": "Biochem", "t": "HOMOCYSTINURIA vs MARFAN SYNDROME - LENS DISLOCATION DIRECTION", "b": "Both conditions cause tall stature, long limbs (arachnodactyly), and lens dislocation, and both involve fibrillin disruption (Marfan: fibrillin-1 mutation; homocystinuria: excess homocysteine chemically disrupts fibrillin disulfide bonds)."}];
